Exercise 18.15: Explain the differences between using declarations and
directives.

Answer:
using declarations only make a name directly accessible in the local scope however using directive makes the entire contents
of a namespace accessible, namespace might include definitions that cannot appear in local scope so a using directive is treated as if it appeared
in the nearest enclosing namespace scope.

Exercise 18.18: Given the following typical definition of swap § 13.3 (p.
517), determine which version of swap is used if mem1 is a string. What if
mem1 is an int? Explain how name lookup works in both cases.
void swap(T v1, T v2)
{
using std::swap;
swap(v1.mem1, v2.mem1);
// swap remaining members of type T
}

Answer:
Finds swap due to the directive then Argument dependent lookup will take place in the std namespace, string will be found
in the std:: namespace and thus swap(std::string&,std::string&) will be called.
For int the same will happen but it won't be found in std namespace and the best match will be called which is swap(int&,int&)

Exercise 18.19: What if the call to swap was std::swap(v1.mem1,
v2.mem1)?

Answer:
Only functions in the std namepsace named swap will be considered, for string and int it will be the same but
if mem1 has it's own swap function it will not be called.

Exercise 18.20: In the following code, determine which function, if any,
matches the call to compute. List the candidate and viable functions. What
type conversions, if any, are applied to the argument to match the parameter
in each viable function?
namespace primerLib {
void compute();
void compute(const void *);
}
using primerLib::compute;
void compute(int);
void compute(double, double = 3.4);
void compute(char*, char* = 0);
void f()
{
compute(0);
}
What would happen if the using declaration were located in main before the call
to compute? Answer the same questions as before.

Answer:
viable functions:
1)compute(int) -- no conversion needed, exact match
2)compute(double) -- conversion to double is needed
3)void compute(const void *) -- conversion to void* is needed
4)void compute(char*, char* = 0) -- conversion to char is needed

Changing the position of the directive would cause the compiler to match to compute(void*)

